functionEntry.name: getCurrentSport
functionEntry.documentation:
Return the sport for which the current activity retrieves heart rate
zone thresholds.

If the active sport does not have sport specific zones, it will return
{Toybox::UserProfile::HR_ZONE_SPORT_GENERIC HR_ZONE_SPORT_GENERIC}.
@example
using Toybox.UserProfile;
var profile = UserProfile.getCurrentSport();
Returns [Toybox::UserProfile::SportHrZone] The current HR zone sport from the

{Toybox::UserProfile::HR_ZONE_SPORT_GENERIC HR_ZONE_SPORT_*} enum.
@since 1.2.6

functionEntry.name: getProfile
functionEntry.documentation:

using Toybox.UserProfile;
var profile = UserProfile.getProfile();
Returns [Toybox::UserProfile::Profile] The Profile object for the

current user
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: getHeartRateZones
functionEntry.documentation:
Retrieve an {Toybox::Lang::Array Array} of the current heart rate zone
threshold values in beats per minute (bpm)

The returned Array contains zone values as follows:
* min zone 1 - The minimum heart rate threshold for zone 1
* max zone 1 - The maximum heart rate threshold for zone 1
* max zone 2 - The maximum heart rate threshold for zone 2
* max zone 3 - The maximum heart rate threshold for zone 3
* max zone 4 - The maximum heart rate threshold for zone 4
* max zone 5 - The maximum heart rate threshold for zone 5
@example Use the HR_ZONE_SPORT_* enum to get the zone for that specific sport
using Toybox.UserProfile;
var genericZoneInfo = UserProfile.getHeartRateZones(UserProfile.HR_ZONE_SPORT_GENERIC);
sport [Toybox::UserProfile::SportHrZone] The sport that zones are being

requested from. Should be a {Toybox::UserProfile::HR_ZONE_SPORT_GENERIC HR_ZONE_SPORT_*} value.
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Array] An Array of zone thresholds for the

requested sport.
@since 1.2.6

functionEntry.name: getUserActivityHistory
functionEntry.documentation:
Get an iterator for Activity history for the user
@example Shows the use of UserActivityHistoryIterator
using Toybox.UserProfile;
using Toybox.System;

// get a UserActivityHistoryIterator object
var userActivityIterator = UserProfile.getUserActivityHistory();
var sample = userActivityIterator.next(); // get the user activity data

while (sample != null) {
System.println("Sample: " + sample.userActivityData); // print the current sample
sample = userActivityIterator.next();
}
Returns [Toybox::UserProfile::UserActivityHistoryIterator] Iterator object

@since 3.3.0

will be called on the registered {Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::BleDelegate BleDelegate} with
the associated {Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::Device Device} object

This pairing does not persist across application instances.

for the device that should be paired. Cannot be +null+.

@throws [Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::DevicePairException] Thrown if

functionEntry.name: registerProfile
functionEntry.documentation:
Registers a Bluetooth Profile Definition

Call this function to define all of the Profiles that will be used in
the application. Only registered characteristics and descriptors will be
available when performing GATT operations

When the operation is completed,
{Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::BleDelegate#onProfileRegister onProfileRegister()}
will be called on the registered {Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::BleDelegate BleDelegate}
with the UUID and a Status.

Registration can fail if too many profiles are registered, the current
limit is 3.

@example
using Toybox.BluetoothLowEnergy;

function registerProfiles() {
var profile = { // Set the Profile
:uuid => Ble.stringToUuid("xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx"),
:characteristics => [ { // Define the characteristics
:uuid => Ble.stringToUuid("xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx"), // UUID of the first characteristic
:descriptors => [ // Descriptors of the characteristic
Ble.stringToUuid("xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx"),
Ble.stringToUuid("xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx") ] }, {
:uuid => Ble.stringToUuid("xxxxxxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx-xxxxxxxxxxxx") }] // UUID of the second characteristic
};

// Make the registerProfile call
BluetoothLowEnergy.registerProfile( profile );
}

profile [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] Profile Definition. Defines

the expected Profile UUID, Profile Characteristics and Characteristic
Descriptors.
Cannot be +null+.

@throws [Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::ProfileRegistrationException] If
registration could not be completed
@since 3.1.0

functionEntry.name: exitTo
functionEntry.documentation:
Exit the current app and launch a new app.

This may only be called by watch-apps and widgets, and may only target
watch-apps (both native activities and Connect IQ apps) and widgets.
This is an asynchronous request that presents a confirmation dialog to
launch the Intent. If confirmed, the current app will exit. Otherwise,
the app will continue to run without exiting.
intent [Toybox::System::Intent] The Intent to trigger

@throws [Toybox::System::UnexpectedAppTypeException] Indicates the intended
application is not a device app or widget
@throws [Toybox::System::AppNotInstalledException] Indicates the intended
application is not installed
@throws [Toybox::System::PreviousOperationNotCompleteException] Indicates
exitTo() is called a second time before the initial call completes
@example
using Toybox.System;
var targetApp = new System.Intent(
"manifest-id://12345678-1234-1234-1234-123412341234",
{"arg"=>"CurrentAppName"}
);
System.exitTo(targetApp);
@see Toybox::System::Intent
@since 2.2.0

functionEntry.name: getLastTemporalEventTime
functionEntry.documentation:
Get the time the last temporal background event was triggered.

This is useful for ensuring new events are not scheduled within the five
minute minimum time allowed between temporal events.
Returns [Toybox::Time::Moment] The time the last background event was

triggered, but may be +null+ if no previous temporal background event
has occurred or if the device app or widget has been started since the
event was last triggered
@example Register a new temporal background event as soon as allowed
using Toybox.Background;
using Toybox.Time;
const FIVE_MINUTES = new Time.Duration(5 * 60);
var lastTime = Background.getLastTemporalEventTime();
if (lastTime != null) {
// Events scheduled for a time in the past trigger immediately
var nextTime = lastTime.add(FIVE_MINUTES);
Background.registerForTemporalEvent(nextTime);
} else {
Background.registerForTemporalEvent(Time.now());
}
@see Toybox::Background#registerForTemporalEvent registerForTemporalEvent()
@see Toybox::Time
@since 2.3.0

functionEntry.name: registerForTemporalEvent
functionEntry.documentation:
Register a background event that triggers at a specific time or at a
regular interval.

Temporal background events may be registered to run at a specific point
in time by providing a {Toybox::Time::Moment Moment} at which the event
should trigger, or may be registered to run at a periodically by
specifying an interval {Toybox::Time::Duration Duration}. If a temporal
event is scheduled for a time in the past, the event will trigger
immediately.

Temporal events cannot be set to occur less than 5 minutes after the
last temporal event occurred. For watch-apps and widgets the 5 minute
restriction is cleared on application startup if the event was specified
using a {Toybox::Time::Moment Moment}.

Only one temporal event may be registered at a time. Calling
+registerForTemporalEvent+ will overwrite any previously registered
temporal events.
time [Toybox::Time::Moment, Toybox::Time::Duration] The specific

Moment in time at which to run a background event, or the interval
Duration at which to repeat a background event
@throws [Toybox::Background::InvalidBackgroundTimeException] Indicates an
application has attempted to schedule a background event which either:
* Occurs less than five minutes after the last background event occurred
* Has a duration of less than five minutes
@example Schedule a background event to run five minutes from now
using Toybox.Background;
using Toybox.Time;
const FIVE_MINUTES = new Time.Duration(5 * 60);
var eventTime = Time.now().add(FIVE_MINUTES);
Background.registerForTemporalEvent(eventTime);
@see Toybox::Time
@since 2.3.0

functionEntry.name: requestApplicationWake
functionEntry.documentation:
Display a confirmation dialog requesting to launch the application to
which the background task belongs.

If the dialog is confirmed, the application will open. If the dialog is
declined, the application will not open and the dialog will be dismissed.
This request is only valid for widget or device app background tasks, and
will be ignored by watch face apps.
{Toybox::Background#exit Background.exit()} must be called at some point
in the background process after this method is invoked because the
confirmation dialog will only trigger after the background task exits.
message [Toybox::Lang::String] The message to display in the dialog

when requesting to launch the app
@throws [Toybox::Background::MessageSizeLimitException] Indicates the
provided message exceeds the size limit (255 Bytes). Note that some
characters may be larger than 1 Byte
@example
using Toybox.Background;
(:background)
class BackgroundServiceDelegate extends System.ServiceDelegate {
function initialize() {
ServiceDelegate.initialize();
}

function onTemporalEvent() {
Background.requestApplicationWake("Launch Cool App?");
Background.exit(null);
}
}
@see Toybox::System::ServiceDelegate
@see Toybox::Background#exit Background.exit()
@since 2.3.0

functionEntry.name: exit
functionEntry.documentation:
Terminates the current background process.

All background processes should call this method when they have completed
the desired tasks. Data passed to this method will either be passed
immediately to the active application if it is running, or will be saved
and passed to the application the next time it runs. Data must be one of
the following types:
* {Toybox::Lang::String String}
* {Toybox::Lang::Number Number}
* {Toybox::Lang::Float Float}
* {Toybox::Lang::Boolean Boolean}
* {Toybox::Lang::Char Char}
* {Toybox::Lang::Long Long}
* {Toybox::Lang::Double Double}
* {Toybox::Lang::Array Array}
* {Toybox::Lang::Dictionary Dictionary}
Arrays and Dictionaries may contain +null+ values or any of the above
listed types. If no data should be passed to the main process, +null+ may
be specified.

This method will exit if called by a background process, but will do
nothing if called by the main application process.

backgroundData [Toybox::Lang::Object] The object to pass to the

main process's
{Toybox::Application::AppBase#onBackgroundData AppBase.onBackgroundData()}
method. Passing +null+ will not override previous data values not yet consumed
by the parent application's AppBase.onBackgroundData() method.
@throws [Toybox::Background::ExitDataSizeLimitException] Indicates the
data provided exceeds the data size limit (approximately 8 KB). If this
exception is caught, the process will not exit and should attempt to
call +Background.exit()+ again with less data.
@since 2.3.0

functionEntry.name: getPressureHistory
functionEntry.documentation:
Get the pressure history for the given period, up to the last
power cycle.

This function always returns the most recent pressure samples. The time
between each {Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorSample SensorSample} in the iterator may
be device dependent.
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] Dictionary of options. Can be

+null+.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number, Toybox::Time::Duration] :period The period
of time from which to retrieve the samples.
* If period is +null+, the entire available history is retrieved
* If period is a {Toybox::Time::Duration Duration}, then the history for the given Duration is retrieved
* If period is a {Toybox::Lang::Number Number}, then the last specified Number of entries are retrieved
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Boolean] :order The order in which to
retrieve the samples.
* If order is +null+, the samples will be {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST}
* Use the ORDER enumeration to explicitly select {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST} or {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_OLDEST_FIRST ORDER_OLDEST_FIRST}
Returns [Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorHistoryIterator] An iterator for

the pressure history for the given period. Samples returned by this
iterator are in Pascals (Pa).
@example Gets a SensoryHistoryIterator and prints out the pressure value from the most recent SensorSample
using Toybox.SensorHistory;
using Toybox.Lang;
using Toybox.System;

// Create a method to get the SensorHistoryIterator object
function getIterator() {
// Check device for SensorHistory compatibility
if ((Toybox has :SensorHistory) && (Toybox.SensorHistory has :getPressureHistory)) {
return Toybox.SensorHistory.getPressureHistory({});
}
return null;
}

// Store the iterator info in a variable. The options are 'null' in
// this case so the entire available history is returned with the
// newest samples returned first.
var sensorIter = getIterator();

// Print out the next entry in the iterator
if (sensorIter != null) {
System.println(sensorIter.next().data);
}
@see Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorHistoryIterator
@see Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorSample
@see Toybox::Lang::Method
@since 2.1.0

functionEntry.name: getStressHistory
functionEntry.documentation:
Get stress history data for the given period

This function always returns the most recent sensor history samples. The time
between each `SensorSample` in the iterator may be device dependent.
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] Dictionary of options. Can be

+null+.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number, Toybox::Time::Duration] :period The
period of time from which to retrieve the samples:
* If +null+, the entire available history is retrieved
* If a {Toybox::Time::Duration Duration}, then the history for the given Duration is retrieved
* If a {Toybox::Lang::Number Number}, then the last specified Number of entries are retrieved
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Boolean] :order The order in which to
retrieve the samples:
* If +null+, the samples will be {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST}
* Use the ORDER_* enumeration to explicitly select {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST} or {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_OLDEST_FIRST ORDER_OLDEST_FIRST}
Returns [Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorHistoryIterator] An iterator for

the stress history for the given period. Samples returned by this
iterator are ranges from 0-100. Higher value indicate higher stress
and lower value indicate lower stress.
and a 100 indicates the body is rested and charged.
@example Shows the use of StressHistoryIterator
using Toybox.ActivityMonitor;
using Toybox.System;

// Create a method to get the SensorHistoryIterator object
function getIterator() {
// Check device for SensorHistory compatibility
if ((Toybox has :SensorHistory) && (Toybox.SensorHistory has :getStressHistory)) {
// Set up the method with parameters
return Toybox.SensorHistory.getStressHistory({});
}
return null;
}

// get stress history iterator object
var stressIterator = getIterator();
var sample = stressIterator.next(); // get the stress data

while (sample != null) {
System.println("Sample: " + sample.data); // print the current sample
sample = stressIterator.next();
}
@see Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorHistoryIterator
@see Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorSample
@see Toybox::Lang::Method
@since 3.3.0

functionEntry.name: getBodyBatteryHistory
functionEntry.documentation:
Get the body battery history for the given period.

This function always returns the most recent sensor history samples. The time
between each `SensorSample` in the iterator may be device dependent.
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] Dictionary of options. Can be

+null+.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number, Toybox::Time::Duration] :period The
period of time from which to retrieve the samples:
* If +null+, the entire available history is retrieved
* If a {Toybox::Time::Duration Duration}, then the history for the given Duration is retrieved
* If a {Toybox::Lang::Number Number}, then the last specified Number of entries are retrieved
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Boolean] :order The order in which to
retrieve the samples:
* If +null+, the samples will be {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST}
* Use the ORDER_* enumeration to explicitly select {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST} or {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_OLDEST_FIRST ORDER_OLDEST_FIRST}
Returns [Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorHistoryIterator] An iterator for

the body battery history for the given period. Samples returned by this
iterator are ranges from 0-100. A 0 indicates that the body is drained
and a 100 indicates the body is rested and charged.
@example Shows the use of BodyBatteryIterator
using Toybox.SensorHistory;
using Toybox.System;

// Create a method to get the SensorHistoryIterator object
function getIterator() {
// Check device for SensorHistory compatibility
if ((Toybox has :SensorHistory) && (Toybox.SensorHistory has :getBodyBatteryHistory)) {
// Set up the method with parameters
return Toybox.SensorHistory.getBodyBatteryHistory({});
}
return null;
}
// get the body battery iterator object
var bbIterator = getIterator();
var sample = bbIterator.next(); // get the body battery data

while (sample != null) {
System.println("Sample: " + sample.data); // print the current sample
sample = bbIterator.next();
}
@see Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorHistoryIterator
@see Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorSample
@see Toybox::Lang::Method
@since 3.3.0

@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number, Toybox::Time::Duration] :period The
period of time from which to retrieve the samples:
* If +null+, the entire available history is retrieved
* If a {Toybox::Time::Duration Duration}, then the history for the given Duration is retrieved
* If a {Toybox::Lang::Number Number}, then the last specified Number of entries are retrieved
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Boolean] :order The order in which to
retrieve the samples:
* If +null+, the samples will be listed {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST}
* Use the ORDER_* enumeration to explicitly select {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST ORDER_NEWEST_FIRST} or {Toybox::SensorHistory::ORDER_OLDEST_FIRST ORDER_OLDEST_FIRST}
Returns [Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorHistoryIterator] An iterator for

the heart rate history for the given period. Samples returned by this
iterator are in beats per minute (bpm).
@example Gets a SensoryHistoryIterator and prints out the heart rate value from the most recent SensorSample
using Toybox.SensorHistory;
using Toybox.Lang;
using Toybox.System;

// Create a method to get the SensorHistoryIterator object
function getIterator() {
// Check device for SensorHistory compatibility
if ((Toybox has :SensorHistory) && (Toybox.SensorHistory has :getHeartRateHistory)) {
return Toybox.SensorHistory.getHeartRateHistory({});
}
return null;
}

// Store the iterator info in a variable. The options are 'null' in
// this case so the entire available history is returned with the
// newest samples returned first.
var sensorIter = getIterator();

// Print out the next entry in the iterator
if (sensorIter != null) {
System.println(sensorIter.next().data);
}

@see Toybox::SensorHistory::SensorSample

functionEntry.name: enableLocationEvents
functionEntry.documentation:
Request a Location event.

Using this API requires enabling the Positioning Permission.
Only Device Apps and Widgets may use this API.
options [Toybox::Lang::Number,Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A LOCATION_* value or {Toybox::Lang::Dictionary} of options.

@option options [Toybox::Position::LocationAcquisitionType] :acquisitionType A LOCATION_* enum value indicating the
position acquisition type to use.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Array] :constellations An array of CONSTELLATION_* enum values
specifying what constellations to enable. If not provided, CONSTELLATION_GPS will be used by default.
listener [Toybox::Lang::Method] A reference to a listener method:

* Called when location updates are received
* Receives a Position.Info object
@option options [Toybox::Position::Configuration] :configuration A CONFIGURATION_* value
specifying what configuration to enable. Only available with ConnectIQ 3.3.6 and later.
@option options [Toybox::Position::PositioningMode] :mode a POSITIONING_MODE_* value specifying the mode to use.
If +null+ POSITIONING_MODE_NORMAL will be used by default.
@throws [Toybox::Lang::InvalidValueException] Thrown if :acquisitionType is invalid, if a
specific CONSTELLATION_* value is not supported by a device, or if an invalid combination of
constellation values are specified.
@note Passing an options {Toybox::Lang::Dictionary Dictionary} is only supported with ConnectIQ 3.2.0 and later.
@note Passing the +:configuration+ option is only supported with ConnectIQ 3.3.6 or later.
@note Multitasking: Location events will be disabled when app enters inacitve state, and re-enabled when is active again.
These state changes are denoted by calls to AppBase.onActive() and AppBase.onInactive().
@example
using Toybox.Position;

var options = {
:acquisitionType => Position.LOCATION_CONTINUOUS
};

if (Position has :POSITIONING_MODE_AVIATION) {
options[:mode] = Position.POSITIONING_MODE_AVIATION;
}

if (Position has :hasConfigurationSupport) {
if (Position has :CONFIGURATION_GPS_GLONASS_GALILEO_BEIDOU_L1_L5) &&
(Position.hasConfigurationSupport(Position.CONFIGURATION_GPS_GLONASS_GALILEO_BEIDOU_L1_L5)) {
options[:configuration] = Position.CONFIGURATION_GPS_GLONASS_GALILEO_BEIDOU_L1_L5;
} else if (Position has :CONFIGURATION_GPS_GLONASS_GALILEO_BEIDOU_L1) &&
(Position.hasConfigurationSupport(Position.CONFIGURATION_GPS_GLONASS_GALILEO_BEIDOU_L1)) {
options[:configuration] = Position.CONFIGURATION_GPS_GLONASS_GALILEO_BEIDOU_L1;
} else if (Position has :CONFIGURATION_GPS) &&
(Position.hasConfigurationSupport(Position.CONFIGURATION_GPS)) {
options[:configuration] = Position.CONFIGURATION_GPS;
}
} else if (Position has :CONSTELLATION_GLONASS) {
// this can fail with InvalidValueException if combination is not supported by device
options[:constellations] = [ Position.CONSTELLATION_GPS, Position.CONSTELLATION_GLONASS ];
} else {
options = Position.LOCATION_CONTINUOUS;
}

// Continuous location updates using selected options
Position.enableLocationEvents(options, method(:onPosition));

function onPosition(info) {
var myLocation = info.position.toDegrees();
}

@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: getInfo
functionEntry.documentation:
Get the current {Toybox::Position::Info Position.Info}.

Using this API requires enabling the Positioning Permission.
This is useful for retrieving the current position info either on demand
or periodically within a {Toybox::Timer::Timer Timer}.
Returns [Toybox::Position::Info]

@example Get position info once per second
using Toybox.Position;
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Timer;
var dataTimer = new Timer.Timer();
dataTimer.start(method(:timerCallback), 1000, true); // A one-second timer
function timerCallback() {
var positionInfo = Position.getInfo();
if (positionInfo has :altitude && positionInfo.altitude != null) {
var altitude = positionInfo.altitude;
System.println("Altitude: " + altitude);
}
}

];
}
Attention.vibrate(vibeData);

functionEntry.name: backlight
functionEntry.documentation:
Control the display backlight.

The backlight will always respect the backlight timeout settings on the device.
Behavior of this feature may also change depending on device settings. For example, if a device is set to activate the back light with key
presses, the backlight will toggle on with key presses even if the app is written to turn off the back light with a key press.

On products that use a gesture enabled display, calling this API will suppress the gesture detection for the period that the backlight is
on. Calling this repeatedly can hold the display on, but if the product has burn in protection an exception will be thrown if you attempt
to keep the display enabled for too long (e.g. over 1 minute).

setting [Toybox::Lang::Boolean, Toybox::Lang::Float]

* If +setting+ is a {Toybox::Lang::Boolean Boolean}, +false+ will disable the backlight and +true+
will enable the backlight at the system backlight level.
* If +setting+ is a {Toybox::Lang::Float Float}, the value 0.0 will disable the backlight and values
greater than 0.0 and less than or equal to 1.0 will enable the backlight at the specified brightness.
@note Passing a {Toybox::Lang::Float Float} is only supported with ConnectIQ 3.2.1 and later.
@throws BacklightOnTooLongException On products with burn in protection, this exception is thrown if the backlight
is held on for too long continuously
@throws InvalidOptionsException If the Float value is outside the valid range.
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: makeWebRequest
functionEntry.documentation:
Initiate a download request.

Web requests are asynchronous. The supplied response callback method
will be called when the request returns.
@example
// It is common for developers to wrap a makeWebRequest() call in a function
// as displayed below. The function defines the variables for each of the
// necessary arguments in a Communications.makeWebRequest() call, then passes
// these variables as the arguments. This allows for a clean layout of your web
// request and expandability.
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Communications;

// set up the response callback function
function onReceive(responseCode, data) {
if (responseCode == 200) {
System.println("Request Successful"); // print success
}
else {
System.println("Response: " + responseCode); // print response code
};

};

function makeRequest() {
var url = "https://www.garmin.com"; // set the url

var params = { // set the parameters
"definedParams" => "123456789abcdefg"
};

var options = { // set the options
:method => Communications.HTTP_REQUEST_METHOD_GET, // set HTTP method
:headers => { // set headers
"Content-Type" => Communications.REQUEST_CONTENT_TYPE_URL_ENCODED},
// set response type
:responseType => Communications.HTTP_RESPONSE_CONTENT_TYPE_URL_ENCODED
};

var responseCallback = method(:onReceive); // set responseCallback to
// onReceive() method
// Make the Communications.makeWebRequest() call
Communications.makeWebRequest(url, params, options, responseCallback);
}
url [Toybox::Lang::String] The URL being requested

parameters [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A Dictionary of keys and

values.
* These values should not be URL encoded.
* Can be +null+.
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A Dictionary of

options.
responseCallback [Toybox::Lang::Method] A reference to

a callback method which must accept two arguments:
* responseCode: The server response code or a BLE_* error type
* data: The content if the request was successful, or +null+
@option options [Toybox::Communications::HttpRequestMethod] :method The HTTP method of the
request. This should be an HTTP_REQUEST_METHOD_* value.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] :headers A Dictionary of HTTP
headers to include in the request.
* The "Content-Type" header for the body of the request can be specified using a {Toybox::Communications REQUEST_CONTENT_TYPE_*} value.
* If the content type is not specified, it will default to "application/json" for GET and DELETE requests, and will default to "application/x-www-form-urlencoded" for POST and PUT requests.
* By default, DELETE requests will have their parameters appended to the URL.
* Setting the method as DELETE as well as a "Content-Type" header will result in the parameters being set in the body of the request and they will not be appended to the URL.
* GET requests can only have their parameters appended to the URL, specifying the "Content-Type" header will not set the body.
@option options [Toybox::Communications::HttpResponseContentType] :responseType The format of the response.
* This should be an {Toybox::Communications HTTP_RESPONSE_CONTENT_TYPE_*} value.
* If HTTP_RESPONSE_CONTENT_TYPE_FIT or HTTP_RESPONSE_CONTENT_TYPE_GPX is given, the system will attempt to download and parse a FIT or GPX file and store the contained data in the device, based on the contents of the file.
* If not given, the system will use the Content-Type header from the server response to determine the format of the response body. If the Content-Type header from the response is not one of the known HTTP_RESPONSE_CONTENT_TYPE_* types, an error will occur.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Object] :context A user-specific context object to be passed to the
response callback. The callback will need to accept a third parameter if this value is
populated.
@option options [Toybox::Media::Encoding] :mediaEncoding The encoding of
the audio content that is being downloaded. Should be a
{Toybox::Media Media.ENCODING_*} value.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :maxBandwidth maximum bandwidth.
TVM will select the audio stream with the highest bandwidth that's less than or equal to the maximum
This option is only effective when processing HLS content
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Method] :fileDownloadProgressCallback
a callback method which must accept two parameters
* totalBytesTransferred: The total number of bytes transferred for the current file download
* fileSize: The size of the file being downloaded. Note that this can be +null+ if file size cannot be determined from the server.
* This option is only supported for media file download progress
* This option is supported since CIQ 3.2.0
@throws [Toybox::Lang::InvalidOptionsException]
Thrown if a required option for a particular request is omitted
@throws [Toybox::Lang::SymbolNotAllowedException]
Thrown if a given :responseType option is not supported for the device the reqest is being made from.
An example would be using HTTP_RESPONSE_CONTENT_TYPE_AUDIO on a device that does not support audio content provider apps
@note This method can be used when connected to WiFi or a mobile device over Bluetooth.
@since 1.3.0

functionEntry.name: makeImageRequest
functionEntry.documentation:
Initiate an image download request.

GCM will scale and dither the image based on the capabilities of the
device, but the user will be able to pass additional options (like
dithering it down to a one color image)
@example
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Communications;

var image;
var responseCode;

// Set up the responseCallback function to return an image or null
function responseCallback(responseCode, data) {
responseCode = responseCode;
if (responseCode == 200) {
image = data;
} else {
image = null;
}
}

// wrap the request in a function
function makeRequest() {
var url = "http://www.garmin.com/image-path"; // set the image url
var parameters = null; // set the parameters
var options = { // set the options
:palette => [ Gfx.COLOR_ORANGE, // set the palette
Gfx.COLOR_DK_BLUE,
Gfx.COLOR_BLUE,
Gfx.COLOR_BLACK ],
:maxWidth => 100, // set the max width
:maxHeight => 100, // set the max height
:dithering => Communications.IMAGE_DITHERING_NONE // set the dithering
};

// Make the image request
Communications.makeImageRequest(url, parameters, options, method(:responseCallback));
}
url [Toybox::Lang::String] The URL of an image to request

parameters [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary, null] The Dictionary of keys and

values
* Appended to the URL
* Can be +null+
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] Additional image options

@option options [Toybox::Lang::Array] :palette The color palette to restrict the image
dithering to. Using a smaller palette can reduce the size of the image
data to speed up transfers
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :maxWidth The maximum width an
image should be scaled to
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :maxHeight The maximum height an
image should be scaled to
@option options [Toybox::Communications::Dithering] :dithering The type of dithering
to use when processing the image. Defaults to
{Toybox::Communications::IMAGE_DITHERING_FLOYD_STEINBERG IMAGE_DITHERING_FLOYD_STEINBERG}
@option options [Toybox::Communications::PackingFormat] :packingFormat The format of the
image data to request. Defaults to
{Toybox::Communications::PACKING_FORMAT_DEFAULT PACKING_FORMAT_DEFAULT}
responseCallback [Toybox::Lang::Method] A reference to a callback

method which must accept two arguments:
* responseCode: The server response code or a BLE_* error type
* data: A {Toybox::WatchUi::BitmapResource BitmapResource} or {Toybox::Graphics::BitmapReference BitmapReference} from a successful request, or +null+ on error
@note This method can be used when connected to WiFi or a mobile device over Bluetooth.
@since 1.2.0

functionEntry.name: makeOAuthRequest
functionEntry.documentation:
Request an OAuth sign-in through Garmin Connect Mobile.

A notification will trigger on the phone, that when clicked, provides a
web view that shows +requestUrl+. If the user grants permission to the app,
then the callback registered by
{Toybox::Communications#registerForOAuthMessages registerForOAuthMessages()}
will be called with an {Toybox::Communications::OAuthMessage OAuthMessage}
from the OAuth response.
@example
using Toybox.Communications;
using Toybox.System;

const CLIENT_ID = "myClientID";
const OAUTH_CODE = "myOAuthCode";
const OAUTH_ERROR = "myOAuthError";

// register a callback to capture results from OAuth requests
Communications.registerForOAuthMessages(method(:onOAuthMessage));

// wrap the OAuth request in a function
function getOAuthToken() {
status = "Look at OAuth screen\n";
Ui.requestUpdate();

// set the makeOAuthRequest parameters
var params = {
"scope" => Comm.encodeURL("https://www.serviceurl.com/"),
"redirect_uri" => "https://localhost",
"response_type" => "code",
"client_id" => $.CLIENT_ID
};

// makeOAuthRequest triggers login prompt on mobile device.
// "responseCode" and "responseError" are the parameters passed
// to the resultUrl. Check the oauth provider's documentation
// to determine the correct strings to use.
Comm.makeOAuthRequest(
"https://requesturl.com",
params,
"http://resulturl.com",
Comm.OAUTH_RESULT_TYPE_URL,
{"responseCode" => $.OAUTH_CODE, "responseError" => $.OAUTH_ERROR}
);
}

// implement the OAuth callback method
function onOAuthMessage(message) {
if (message.data != null) {
var code = message.data[$.OAUTH_CODE];
var error = message.data[$.OAUTH_ERROR];
} else {
// return an error
}
}
// the OAuth service can now be used with a makeWebRequest() call
requestUrl [Toybox::Lang::String] The URL to load in the web view

to begin authentication
requestParams [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] Non-URL encoded parameters

for the +requestUrl+
resultUrl [Toybox::Lang::String] The URL of the final page of

authentication that contains the +resultKeys+
resultType [Toybox::Lang::TokenResult] An OAUTH_RESULT_TYPE_* value

that specifies the format of the result
resultKeys [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] The desired OAuth response

values passed to the callback method. The keys map to the actual OAuth
response keys, and the values map to the keys of the
{Toybox::Communications::OAuthMessage OAuthMessage} data.
@note This method can only be used when connected to a mobile device over Bluetooth.
@since 1.3.0

functionEntry.name: createSession
functionEntry.documentation:
Create a {Toybox::ActivityRecording::Session Session} object with
options determined by the caller.

Only one Session object is allowed to exist at a time. If there
is an existing object that has not been closed using the
{Toybox::ActivityRecording::Session#save save()} or
{Toybox::ActivityRecording::Session#discard discard()} methods, this method will
return that object instead of creating a new one. On some products
running the 1.x virtual machine, creating a Session object requires a
large memory allocation. To free this memory, the Session must first be
successfully saved or discarded, and then app references to the Session
object should be set to +null+.
@example Create a Session with auto lap detection using entry/exit lines
using Toybox.ActivityRecording;
function createSession() {
var session = ActivityRecording.createSession({ // set up recording session
:name=>"Race", // set session name
:sport=>Activity.SPORT_GENERIC, // set sport type
:subSport=>Activity.SUB_SPORT_GENERIC, // set sub sport type
:autoLap=>{ // auto lap configuration
:type=>:lines, // auto lap using entry/exit lines
:exit=>[loc1, loc2], // set exit of auto lap staging box (typically the finish line)
:entry=>[loc3, loc4], // set entrance of auto lap staging box (typically before the finish line)
:autoStart=>true // auto start using the entry/exit lines
}
});
return session;
}
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A Dictionary containing

session creation options.
@option options [Toybox::ActivityRecording::Sport, Toybox::Activity::Sport] :sport The primary sport being
recorded (SPORT_GENERIC by default).
@option options [Toybox::ActivityRecording::SubSport, Toybox::Activity::SubSport] :subSport The sport subcategory
being recorded (SUB_SPORT_GENERIC by default).
@option options [Toybox::Lang::String] :name Required. This is the name
that will be associated with the sport being recorded. The suggested
maximum length of the name is 15 characters (some devices support
longer names).
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Float] :poolLength This is the length of
the pool in meters for this activity. If this session object is configured
with +:sport=>SPORT_SWIMMING+ and +:subSport=>SUB_SPORT_LAP_SWIMMING+, this
option is required to configure the system in this mode. If it is not
provided, activity data may have undefined behavior. For all other sport
modes, this option is ignored.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] :autoLap A dictionary containing
auto-lap detection options. If present, this dictionary must have a +:type+ key;
If the value of +:type+ is +:lines+, the +:entry+ and +:exit+ keys are required. The
values associated with +:entry+ and +:exit+ describe the endpoints of the auto lap
entry and exit line segments, each being defined as an {Toybox::Lang::Array Array}
of two {Toybox::Position::Location Location} objects. (added in 3.0.10)
@option options [Toybox::SensorLogging::SensorLogger] :sensorLogger The
SensorLogger to use to record this session.
@throws [Toybox::Lang::InvalidOptionsException] Thrown if required options
are missing or provided options are invalid in +:autoLap+ options dictionary
Returns [Toybox::ActivityRecording::Session] A new Session object, or

the existing Session object if a Session is active and has not been
saved or discarded.
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: registerForOAuthMessages
functionEntry.documentation:
Register a callback for receiving OAuth messages.

The callback will be called once for each received OAuth message.
If there are messages waiting for the app when this function is
called, the callback will immediately be called once for each waiting
message.
method [Toybox::Lang::Method] A reference to a callback, which

must receive a +data+ argument of the type
{Toybox::Authentication::OAuthMessage OAuthMessage}.
@example
using Toybox.Authentication;

function onOAuthMessage(message) {
if (message.data != null) {
var code = message.data[OAUTH_CODE];
var error = message.data[OAUTH_ERROR];
} else {
// return an error
}
}
Authentication.registerForOAuthMessages(method(:onOAuthMessage));

@since 3.3.0

functionEntry.name: makeOAuthRequest
functionEntry.documentation:
Request an OAuth sign-in through Garmin Connect IQ Mobile App

A notification will trigger on the phone, that when clicked, provides a
web view that shows +requestUrl+. If the user grants permission to the app,
then the callback registered by
{Toybox::Authentication#registerForOAuthMessages registerForOAuthMessages()}
will be called with an {Toybox::Authentication::OAuthMessage OAuthMessage}
from the OAuth response.
@example
using Toybox.Authentication;
using Toybox.System;

const CLIENT_ID = "myClientID";
const OAUTH_CODE = "myOAuthCode";
const OAUTH_ERROR = "myOAuthError";

// register a callback to capture results from OAuth requests
Authentication.registerForOAuthMessages(method(:onOAuthMessage));

// wrap the OAuth request in a function
function getOAuthToken() {
status = "Look at OAuth screen\n";
Ui.requestUpdate();

// set the makeOAuthRequest parameters
var params = {
"redirect_uri" => "connectiq://oauth",
"response_type" => "code",
"client_id" => $.CLIENT_ID
};

// makeOAuthRequest triggers login prompt on mobile device.
// "responseCode" and "responseError" are the parameters passed
// to the resultUrl. Check the oauth provider's documentation
// to determine the correct strings to use.
Auth.makeOAuthRequest(
"https://requesturl.com",
params,
"http://resulturl.com",
Auth.OAUTH_RESULT_TYPE_URL,
{"responseCode" => $.OAUTH_CODE, "responseError" => $.OAUTH_ERROR}
);
}

// implement the OAuth callback method
function onOAuthMessage(message) {
if (message.data != null) {
var code = message.data[$.OAUTH_CODE];
var error = message.data[$.OAUTH_ERROR];
} else {
// return an error
}
}
// the OAuth service can now be used with a makeWebRequest() call
requestUrl [Toybox::Lang::String] The URL to load in the web view

to begin authentication
requestParams [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] Non-URL encoded parameters

for the +requestUrl+
resultUrl [Toybox::Lang::String] The URL of the final page of

authentication that contains the +resultKeys+
resultType [Toybox::Authentication::OAuthResultType] An OAUTH_RESULT_TYPE_* value

that specifies the format of the result
resultKeys [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] The desired OAuth response

values passed to the callback method. The keys map to the actual OAuth
response keys, and the values map to the keys of the
{Toybox::Authentication::OAuthMessage OAuthMessage} data.
@since 3.3.0

functionEntry.name: animate
functionEntry.documentation:
Animate an Object.

Animate works by changing an object property over time, such as the
x-position of a Drawable. The animation starts after the call and runs
the length of the specified period. During this time, the View object's
onUpdate() method will be invoked at an increased rate to facilitate
animation.
object [Toybox::Lang::Object] The object to animate

property [Toybox::Lang::Symbol] The Symbol of the object's property

to animate (e.g. :locX, :locY, etc.)
type [Toybox::WatchUi::AnimationType] A

{Toybox::WatchUi::ANIM_TYPE_LINEAR WatchUi.ANIM_TYPE_*} value
start [Toybox::Lang::Number] The starting value of the property

stop [Toybox::Lang::Number] The ending value of the property

period [Toybox::Lang::Float] The duration of the animation in seconds

callback [Toybox::Lang::Method] A Method to call when the animation

is complete; this can be +null+
@example Move a bitmap across the screen from left to right
using System.WatchUi;

square = new Ui.Bitmap({
:rezId=>Rez.Drawables.square,
:locX=>10,
:locY=>30
});
WatchUi.animate(square, :locX, Ui.ANIM_TYPE_LINEAR, 10, 200, 10, null);
@note Will cause an app crash if called from background or data field app,
or from watch face while in low power mode
@see Toybox::WatchUi::Drawable
@see Toybox::WatchUi::Bitmap
@since 1.0.0

must receive a +data+ argument of the type
{Toybox::Notifications::NotificationMessage NotificationMessage}.

functionEntry.name: registerSensorDataListener
functionEntry.documentation:
Register a callback to fetch high-frequency data from various sensors.

The callback will get invoked each time a new set of sensor data over
the length of time specified in the period option is available.
@note Only one data request is allowed to be registered at a time.
Subsequent calls to this function for the same sensor type will
override previously registered requests.
listener [Toybox::Lang::Method] A method that takes a single

{Toybox::Sensor::SensorData SensorData} object as a parameter
that will contain the requested data.
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A Dictionary of options.

The allowed values depend on sensor type.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :period Period of time to request
samples in seconds. Maximum is 4 seconds.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] :accelerometer Options for
accelerometer data.
* :enabled ({Toybox::Lang::Boolean Toybox::Lang::Boolean}) Set to +true+
to fetch data from the accelerometer.
* :sampleRate ({Toybox::Lang::Number Toybox::Lang::Number}) Samples per
second to request in Hz.
* :includePower ({Toybox::Lang::Boolean Toybox::Lang::Boolean}) Valid
only when +:accelerometer=>:enabled+ is set to +true+. Requests that
the {Toybox::Sensor::AccelerometerData#power power Array} be computed.
* :includePitch ({Toybox::Lang::Boolean Toybox::Lang::Boolean}) Valid
only when +:accelerometer=>:enabled+ is set to +true+. Requests that
the {Toybox::Sensor::AccelerometerData#pitch pitch Array} be computed.
* :includeRoll ({Toybox::Lang::Boolean Toybox::Lang::Boolean}) Valid
only when +:accelerometer=>:enabled+ is set to +true+. Requests that
the {Toybox::Sensor::AccelerometerData#roll roll Array} be computed.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] :heartBeatIntervals Options for
Heart Beat Interval data.
* :enabled ({Toybox::Lang::Boolean Toybox::Lang::Boolean}) Set to +true+
to fetch heart beat interval data.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] :gyroscope Options for
gyroscope data.
* :enabled ({Toybox::Lang::Boolean Toybox::Lang::Boolean}) Set to +true+
to fetch data from the gyroscope.
* :sampleRate ({Toybox::Lang::Number Toybox::Lang::Number}) Samples per
second to request in Hz.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] :magnetometer Options for
magnetometer data.
* :enabled ({Toybox::Lang::Boolean Toybox::Lang::Boolean}) Set to +true+
to fetch data from the magnetometer.
* :sampleRate ({Toybox::Lang::Number Toybox::Lang::Number}) Samples per
second to request in Hz.
@throws {Toybox::Sensor::TooManySensorDataListenersException}
Thrown if more than one listener is tried to register for sensor data.
@throws {Toybox::Lang::InvalidOptionsException}
Thrown if any required options are excluded, if provided options are out
of range, or are of the wrong type.
@example
using Toybox.Sensor;
// initialize accelerometer
var options = {
:period => 1, // 1 second sample time
:accelerometer => {
:enabled => true, // Enable the accelerometer
:sampleRate => 25 // 25 samples
},
:heartBeatIntervals => {
:enabled => true
}
};
// Using the callback setup in Toybox.SensorHistory.SensorData
Sensor.registerSensorDataListener(method(:accelCallback), options);
@see Toybox::ActivityRecording#createSession ActivityRecording.createSession()
@see Toybox::Sensor::SensorData
@note Will cause an app crash if called from a data field app
@since 2.3.0

functionEntry.documentation:
Enable sensors for use.

This will enable both connected ANT+ sensors and system sensors if possible.
sensors [Toybox::Lang::Array] The sensors to enable:

* An Array of SENSOR_* types to enable
* An empty array ([]) to disable all sensors
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Array] An Array of requested sensors that are available

using Toybox.Sensor;
Sensor.setEnabledSensors([Sensor.SENSOR_HEARTRATE]);
@note Will cause an app crash if called from a data field app

and sensor enabled during active mode will be disabled when app becomes inactive,

functionEntry.name: enableSensorEvents
functionEntry.documentation:
Request sensor events from enabled sensors.

Sensor events are retrieved from any enabled sensors at a rate of 1 Hz.
The data retrieved from enabled sensors is passed to the listener
{Toybox::Lang::Method Method} provided as a parameter to this method.
listener [Toybox::Lang::Method] A reference to a listener Method:

* Called when sensor updates are received
* Receives a Sensor.info object
* Use +null+ to specify no listener
@example

// Given an onSensor listener method is defined
Sensor.enableSensorEvents(method(:onSensor));
@note Will cause an app crash if called from a data field app
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: getInfo
functionEntry.documentation:
Get the current Sensor {Toybox::Sensor::Info Sensor.Info}.

This is useful for retrieving the current sensor info either on demand
or periodically within a {Toybox::Timer::Timer Timer}.
Returns [Toybox::Sensor::Info]

@example Get accelerometer data once per second
using Toybox.Sensor;
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Timer;
var dataTimer = new Timer.Timer();
dataTimer.start(method(:timerCallback), 1000, true); // A one-second timer
function timerCallback() {
var sensorInfo = Sensor.getInfo();
if (sensorInfo has :accel && sensorInfo.accel != null) {
var accel = sensorInfo.accel;
var xAccel = accel[0];
var yAccel = accel[1];
System.println("x: " + xAccel + ", y: " + yAccel);
}
}
@see Toybox::Timer::Timer
@note Will cause an app crash if called from a data field app
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: isBackgroundScanEnabled
functionEntry.documentation:
See if background scanning is enabled for the channel assignment.
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Boolean] Returns +true+ if background scan is

enabled, otherwise +false+.
@example
using Toybox.Ant;
// Assuming initialized channel

@since 1.2.0

functionEntry.name: initialize
functionEntry.documentation:
Constructor
By default disables background scanning.
c [Toybox::Ant::ChannelType] The channel type specifier. Must use one

of the following constants:
* {Toybox::Ant::CHANNEL_TYPE_TX_NOT_RX CHANNEL_TYPE_TX_NOT_RX} - Bidirectional Transmit (Master)
* Master Channels are not allowed on the ANT+ Network
* {Toybox::Ant::CHANNEL_TYPE_RX_NOT_TX CHANNEL_TYPE_RX_NOT_TX} - Bidirectional Receive (Slave)
* {Toybox::Ant::CHANNEL_TYPE_RX_ONLY CHANNEL_TYPE_RX_ONLY} - Receive Only (Slave)
n [Toybox::Ant::NetworkType] The network type specifier. Must use one of

the following constants:
* {Toybox::Ant::NETWORK_PUBLIC NETWORK_PUBLIC} - ANT public network
* {Toybox::Ant::NETWORK_PLUS NETWORK_PLUS} - ANT+ network
* {Toybox::Ant::NETWORK_PRIVATE NETWORK_PRIVATE} - ANT private network
* A network key must be provided for an Private Network
* Both 64 and 128 bit keys are required
@example
using Toybox.Ant;

var channelType = Ant.CHANNEL_TYPE_RX_NOT_TX // Bidirectional Receive (Slave)
var network = Ant.NETWORK_PUBLIC; // Ant public network
// Get the channel
channelAssign = new Ant.ChannelAssignment(channelType, network);

// Initialize the channel - assumes message callback method
GenericChannel.initialize(method(:onMessage), channelAssign);
@see Toybox::AntPlus
@since 1.0.0

is an 8-byte {Toybox::Lang::Array Array} of numbers
@example
using Toybox.Ant;
// create a data Array to format Message
var data = new[8];
for (var i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
data[i] = i + 1; // Set the values of each member
}
var message = new Ant.Message();
message.setPayload(data); // Assumes valid data

// Assumes a valid GenericChannel object
genericChannel.sendBroadcast(message);
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Boolean] +true+ on success, otherwise +false+.

@see Toybox::Ant::Message

functionEntry.name: sendBurst
functionEntry.documentation:
Send an {Toybox::Lang::Array Array} of
{Toybox::Ant::Message Messages} as a burst across the ANT channel.

Success or Fail is received by the {Toybox::Ant::BurstListener BurstListener}.
burstData [Toybox::Ant::BurstPayload] The data to burst across

the channel
@example
using Toybox.Ant;
var burstData = new Ant.BurstPayload(); // Create new payload

// Message must contain a valid payload
burstData.add(message); // Add Message object to payload

// Assumes a valid GenericChannel object
genericChannel.sendBurst(burstData); // Send Message
@see Toybox::Ant::BurstPayload
@throws [Toybox::Lang::SymbolNotAllowedException] Thrown if called from a
data field app
@since 2.2.0

functionEntry.name: sendAcknowledge
functionEntry.documentation:
Send an acknowledge message.

You can expect to receive either
{Toybox::Ant::MSG_CODE_EVENT_TRANSFER_TX_COMPLETED MSG_CODE_EVENT_TRANSFER_TX_COMPLETED} or
{Toybox::Ant::MSG_CODE_EVENT_TRANSFER_TX_FAILED MSG_CODE_EVENT_TRANSFER_TX_FAILED} if
the message succeeded/failed going to the recipient.
data [Toybox::Ant::Message] A message whose payload

is an 8-byte {Toybox::Lang::Array Array} of numbers
@example
using Toybox.Ant;
// create a data Array to format Message
var data = new[8];
for (var i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
data[i] = i + 1; // Set the values of each member
}
var message = new Ant.Message();
message.setPayload(data); // Assumes valid data

// Assumes a valid GenericChannel object
genericChannel.sendAcknowledge(message);
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Boolean] +true+ on success, otherwise +false+.

@see Toybox::Ant::Message
@since 1.0.0

Constructor
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] The initialization options

@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :deviceNumber The ANT-id of
the device to search for. Not setting enables a wild card search
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :deviceType 1-Byte device
type identifier
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :transmissionType The
manufacturer-specific transport type and extended device number
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :messagePeriod The message period
that the sensor uses
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :radioFrequency The radio
frequency that the sensor operates on. Range of 2 to 80.
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :searchTimeoutLowPriority The
Low Priority search timeout that a receiving channel will wait for
in order to start tracking a master
* Low Priority search provides the capability of searching for a master without interrupting other channels on the device
* Range of 0 to 12 (2.5s increments)
* Default 6 (15s)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :searchTimeoutHighPriority The
High Priority search timeout that a receiving channel will wait for
in order to start tracking a master
* Is triggered after the Low Priority search mode times out
* Will interrupt other channels
* Will take priority over any other open channels on that device
* If it overlaps another channel the High Priority search takes priority and that other channel is blocked
* Keeping this search type disabled unless you have great difficulty acquiring a master through Low Priority search is recommended
* High Priority searches are disabled in data-fields, and will be ignored for that application type
* Range of 0 to 2 (2.5s increments)
* Default 0 (disabled)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :searchThreshold A proximity
threshold bin as a Number
* Configures the RSSI threshold a slave channel will search for which is effectively the distance at which a slave is willing to be from a master
* Values are 0 (disabled), 1 (closest), 10 (farthest)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :networkKey64Bit 64 bit
network key
* Set this when {Toybox::Ant::NETWORK_PRIVATE NETWORK_PRIVATE} was chosen in the channel assignment
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :networkKey128Bit 128 bit
network key
* Set this when NETWORK_PRIVATE was chosen in the channel assignment
@since 1.2.0
@see https://www.thisisant.com/developer/resources/downloads/ ANT Downloads & Resources - ANT Message Protocol and Usage

functionEntry.name: add
functionEntry.documentation:
Add a {Toybox::Time::Moment Moment} or another Duration to a Duration.

When adding a Moment to a Duration, this method functions the same as
the {Toybox::Time::Moment#add Moment.add()} method.
time [Toybox::Time::Duration, Toybox::Time::Moment] The Duration

or Moment to add to Duration
Returns [Toybox::Time::Duration, Toybox::Time::Moment] A Duration or

Moment object that is the sum of self and the provided object:
* Duration + Moment = Moment
* Duration + Duration = Duration
@example Add two Duration objects
using Toybox.Time;
var oneHour = new Time.Duration(3600);
var twoHours = new Time.Duration(7200);
var threeHours = oneHour.add(twoHours);
@see Toybox::Time::Moment#add Moment.add()
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: compare
functionEntry.documentation:
Determine if a Duration is shorter or longer than another Duration.

This computes a Number representing the difference between the two
Duration objects in seconds. The {Toybox::Time::Duration#subtract subtract()}
method can also be used to get the absolute difference between two
Duration objects.
duration [Toybox::Time::Duration] The Duration to compare to

this Duration
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Number] The Number of seconds difference between

the two Duration objects. If the Duration supplied for comparison is
longer than this Duration, the value will be negative.
@example
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Time;
var oneHour = new Time.Duration(3600);
var twoHours = new Time.Duration(7200);

System.println(oneHour.compare(twoHours)); // -3600, or one minute in the past
System.println(twoHours.compare(oneHour)); // 3600, or one minute in the future
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: moment
functionEntry.documentation:
Create a {Toybox::Time::Moment Moment} from a Dictionary of options.
Each option value is assumed to be in the UTC time zone.

Unlike {Toybox::Time::Moment#initialize Moment.initialize()}, which
is based on the UNIX epoch, a Moment created with Gregorian.moment()
is based on {Toybox::Time#today today()}. The result is determined
by taking the result of {Toybox::Time#today today()} and overlaying
the options provided.

options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A dictionary of options;

values that would not result in a valid date are not allowed
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :year The year (1970-2106)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number, Toybox::Lang::Symbol] :month The month (1-12) or a Symbol (:january, :february, ...)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :day The day of month (1-31)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :hour The hour (0-23)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :minute The minute (0-59)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :second The second (0-59)
Returns [Toybox::Time::Moment] A Moment representing the specified

moment in time
@example Create a Moment representing midnight on the first day of the current month.
using Toybox.Time;
var oneDay = Gregorian.moment({:day => 1});
@see Toybox::Time::Moment#initialize Moment.initialize()
@see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coordinated_Universal_Time UTC Time
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: duration
functionEntry.documentation:
Create a {Toybox::Time::Duration Duration} from a Dictionary of options.

This is an alternative to
{Toybox::Time::Duration#initialize Duration.initialize()} that allows
the Duration to be made more easily, using familiar units, which can
be handy when building a Duration manually.

Option values are represented as signed 32-bit integers.
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A dictionary of options

@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :years The number of years
(max 69)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :days The number of days
(max 24855)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :hours The number of hours
(max 596523)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :minutes The number of minutes
(max 35791394)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :seconds The number of seconds
(max 2147483647)
Returns [Toybox::Time::Duration] The Duration representing the

specified span of time
@example Create a Duration of one day with Gregorian.duration()
using Toybox.Time.Gregorian;
var oneDay = Gregorian.duration({:days => 1});
@see Toybox::Time::Duration#initialize Duration.initialize()
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: info
functionEntry.documentation:
Get {Toybox::Time::Gregorian::Info Info} for a {Toybox::Time::Moment Moment}
in local time.
moment [Toybox::Time::Moment, Toybox::Time::LocalMoment] A Moment

or LocalMoment object for which to get Info
format [Toybox::Time::DateFormat] A Time.FORMAT_* type

Returns [Toybox::Time::Gregorian::Info] Info for the supplied Moment

formatted according to the specified format type in local time.
@example Get Info for today in local time (assume CST)
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Time;
using Toybox.Time.Gregorian;
var options = {
:year => 2003,
:month => 5, // 3.x devices can also use :month => Gregorian.MONTH_MAY
:day => 16,
:hour => 0
};
var date = Gregorian.moment(options);
var birthday = Gregorian.info(date, Time.FORMAT_MEDIUM);
System.println(birthday.year); // 2003
System.println(birthday.month); // May
System.println(birthday.day); // 16
System.println(birthday.hour); // 19
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: compare
functionEntry.documentation:
Determine if a LocalMoment is before or after another LocalMoment

This computes a Number representing the difference between the two
LocalMoment objects in seconds. The {Toybox::Time::LocalMoment#subtract subtract()}
method can also be used to get the absolute Duration between two LocalMoment
objects.
moment [Toybox::Time::LocalMoment] The LocalMoment to compare

to this LocalMoment
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Number] The Number of seconds difference between

the two LocalMoment objects, without considering time zone rules. If
the LocalMoment supplied for comparison is after this LocalMoment, the
value will be negative.
@example
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Time;
using Toybox.Time.Gregorian;
using Toybox.Position;

var where = new Position.Location({
:latitude => 38.85391,
:longitude => -94.79630,
:format => :degrees,
});
var today = Gregorian.localMoment(where, Time.today());
var oneDay = new Time.Duration(Gregorian.SECONDS_PER_DAY);
var tomorrow = today.add(oneDay);

System.println(today.compare(tomorrow)); // -86400, or one day in the past
System.println(tomorrow.compare(today)); // 86400, or one day in the future
@see Toybox::Time::LocalMoment#subtract LocalMoment.subtract()
@see Toybox::Time::Gregorian::SECONDS_PER_DAY SECONDS_PER_DAY
@since 3.3.0

functionEntry.name: compare
functionEntry.documentation:
Determine if a Moment is before or after another Moment.

This computes a Number representing the difference between the two
Moment objects in seconds. The {Toybox::Time::Moment#subtract subtract()}
method can also be used to get the absolute Duration between two Moment
objects.
moment [Toybox::Time::Moment] The Moment to compare to this

Moment
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Number] The Number of seconds difference between

the two Moment objects. If the Moment supplied for comparison is after
this Moment, the value will be negative.
@example
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Time;
using Toybox.Time.Gregorian;
var today = new Time.Moment(Time.today().value());
var oneDay = new Time.Duration(Gregorian.SECONDS_PER_DAY);
var tomorrow = today.add(oneDay);

System.println(today.compare(tomorrow)); // -86400, or one day in the past
System.println(tomorrow.compare(today)); // 86400, or one day in the future
@see Toybox::Time::Moment#subtract Moment.subtract()
@see Toybox::Time::Gregorian::SECONDS_PER_DAY SECONDS_PER_DAY
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: subtract
functionEntry.documentation:
Subtract a {Toybox::Time::Duration Duration} or
{Toybox::Time::Moment Moment} from a Moment.

subtrahend [Toybox::Time::Moment, Toybox::Time::Duration] The

Moment or Duration to subtract from this Moment
Returns [Toybox::Time::Duration, Toybox::Time::Moment] The Duration

between the two Moment objects or the Moment offset by a Duration.

When subtracting Moments, the computed Duration is always a positive
value. The {Toybox::Time::Moment#compare compare()} method can be
used to determine whether one Moment is before or after another Moment.
@note Subtracting a Duration from a Moment was not supported until
ConnectIQ 3.0.0. If backward compatibility is a concern, it may be
best to add a negative Duration instead.
@example
using Toybox.System;
using Toybox.Time;
using Toybox.Time.Gregorian;
var today = new Time.Moment(Time.today().value());
var oneDay = new Time.Duration(Gregorian.SECONDS_PER_DAY);
var tomorrow = today.add(oneDay);

var duration1 = today.subtract(tomorrow);
var duration2 = tomorrow.subtract(today);

System.println(duration1.value()); // 86400, or one day
System.println(duration2.value()); // 86400, or one day
@see Toybox::Time::Moment#compare Moment.compare()
@see Toybox::Time::Gregorian::SECONDS_PER_DAY SECONDS_PER_DAY
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.documentation:
Requests a write operation

Once the operation is completed,
{Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::BleDelegate#onCharacteristicWrite onCharacteristicWrite()}
will be called on the registered {Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::BleDelegate BleDelegate}
with the status of the operation

Support for long writes is not implemented. Requesting a write on a
characteristic longer than 20 bytes will cause an
{Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::InvalidRequestException InvalidRequestException}

value [Toybox::Lang::ByteArray] New value to store.

options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A Dictionary containing write options

@option options [Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::WriteType] :writeType A
{Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::WRITE_TYPE_WITH_RESPONSE WRITE_TYPE_*}
indicating the write type to use when writing to the characteristic. Cannot be +null+.
@throws [Toybox::BluetoothLowEnergy::InvalidRequestException] if the request is invalid
@since 3.1.0

functionEntry.name: debug
functionEntry.documentation:
Write a debug {Toybox::Lang::String String} to the output stream.

The String is prefixed with DEBUG and a time stamp.
str [Toybox::Lang::String] The String output to the console

@example
using Toybox.Test;
(:test)
function aDebugTest(logger) {
logger.debug("This is a debug message.");
return true;
}
// Output:
DEBUG (9:23): This is a debug message.
@since 2.1.0

using Toybox.Test;
(:test)
function aWarningTest(logger) {

return true;
}
// Output:
WARNING (9:23): This is a warning message.
@since 2.1.0

functionEntry.name: initialize
functionEntry.documentation:
Constructor

A KeyPair can be initialized from a private key by passing a
private key {Toybox::Lang::ByteArray ByteArray} from an initialized
{Toybox::Cryptography::Key Key} object into the +:privateKey+ option
of the initialize method for this class. If no private key is provided,
then both a private and public key will be generated using the required
+:algorithm+ option.
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A dictionary of options

@option options [Toybox::Cryptography::KeyPairAlgorithm] :algorithm The algorithm
to use as a {Toybox::Cryptography::KEY_PAIR_ELLIPTIC_CURVE_SECP224R1 KEY_PAIR_*}
constant (required)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::ByteArray] :privateKey The private
key to be used to generate the KeyPair (optional)
@throws [Toybox::Lang::InvalidOptionsException] Thrown if the
specified +:algorithm+ is not supported, or if a required option is
not provided
@throws [Toybox::Lang::InvalidValueException] Thrown if the specified
+:privateKey+ is not the correct size for the selected algorithm
@note privateKey is expected to be in little-endian byte order.
@since 3.0.0

functionEntry.name: encrypt
functionEntry.documentation:
Encrypt data with the key, depending on how the cipher was initialized.

Encryption can be broken up into two or more calls to encrypt. For
MODE_CBC, the +plaintext+ length (in bytes) must be a multiple of the
block size.
plaintext [Toybox::Lang::ByteArray] The piece of data to encrypt

Returns [Toybox::Lang::ByteArray] The encrypted data

@throws [Toybox::Lang::UnexpectedTypeException] Thrown if a type other
than {Toybox::Lang::ByteArray ByteArray} is provided
@throws [Toybox::Cryptography::InvalidBlockSizeException] Thrown if
+plaintext+ is not a valid size for the selected encryption type
@since 3.0.0

functionEntry.name: initialize
functionEntry.documentation:
Constructor
options [Toybox::Lang::Dictionary] A Dictionary of options

@option options [Toybox::Cryptography::CipherAlgorithm] :algorithm The
encryption type this cipher object will use from the
{Toybox::Cryptography CIPHER_*} enumeration (required)
@option options [Toybox::Cryptography::EncryptionMode] :mode The encryption mode
this cipher object will use from the
{Toybox::Cryptography MODE_*} enumeration (required)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::ByteArray] :key The secret key to use
in the cipher. The key must be of the appropriate length for the
encryption type selected (required)
@option options [Toybox::Lang::ByteArray] :iv The initialization vector
to use for encryption or decryption. This will be generated by the
system using secure random bytes for algorithms that require
it if it is not provided (optional)
@throws [Toybox::Lang::UnexpectedTypeException] Thrown if a type
other than {Toybox::Lang::ByteArray ByteArray} is provided for
the +:key+ and +:iv+ options
@throws [Toybox::Lang::InvalidOptionsException] Thrown if a required
option is not provided, the +:algorithm+ and +:mode+ options are
not initialized with a valid enumeration, an invalid key size is
provided for the selected algorithm, or an invalid initialization
vector size is provided for the selected algorithm
@since 3.0.0

functionEntry.name: decrypt
functionEntry.documentation:
Decrypt data with the key, depending on how the cipher was initialized.

Decryption can be broken up into two or more calls to decrypt(). For
MODE_CBC, the +ciphertext+ length (in bytes) must be a multiple of the

ciphertext [Toybox::Lang::ByteArray] The piece of data to decrypt

Returns [Toybox::Lang::ByteArray] The decrypted data

@throws [Toybox::Lang::UnexpectedTypeException] Thrown if a type other
than {Toybox::Lang::ByteArray ByteArray} is provided
@throws [Toybox::Cryptography::InvalidBlockSizeException] Thrown if
+ciphertext+ is not a valid size for the selected encryption type
@since 3.0.0

functionEntry.name: toDegrees
functionEntry.documentation:
Get a Location object's coordinates in degrees.
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Array] An Array containing the latitude and

longitude as {Toybox::Lang::Double Doubles} in a degree format
@example
using Toybox.Position;
using Toybox.System;
Position.enableLocationEvents(Position.LOCATION_ONE_SHOT, method(:onPosition));

function onPosition(info) {
var myLocation = info.position.toDegrees();
System.println(myLocation[0]); // latitude (e.g. 38.856147)
System.println(myLocation[1]); // longitude (e.g -94.800953)
}
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: initialize
functionEntry.documentation:
Constructor
Create a Location based on a set of coordinates.
options [Toybox::Lang::Array] An Array of options

@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :latitude The latitude
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Number] :longitude The longitude
@option options [Toybox::Lang::Symbol] :format The format of the provided latitude
and longitude as one of three possible values:
* :degrees
* :radians
* :semicircles
@example
using Toybox.Position;
var myLocation = new Position.Location(
{
:latitude => 38.856147,
:longitude => -94.800953,
:format => :degrees
}
);
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: toRadians
functionEntry.documentation:
Get a location object's coordinates in radians.
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Array] An Array containing latitude and longitude

as {Toybox::Lang::Double Doubles} in a radian format
@example
using Toybox.Position;
using Toybox.System;
Position.enableLocationEvents(Position.LOCATION_ONE_SHOT, method(:onPosition));

function onPosition(info) {
var myLocation = info.position.toRadians();
System.println(myLocation[0]); // latitude (e.g. 0.678197)
System.println(myLocation[1]); // longitude (e.g -1.654588)
}
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: toGeoString
functionEntry.documentation:
Get a String representation a Location object's coordinates.
format [Toybox::Position::CoordinateFormat] A Position.GEO_* value

Returns [Toybox::Lang::String] A formatted coordinate String in the

specified format
@example
using Toybox.Position;
using Toybox.System;

:longitude => -94.800953,
:format => :degrees

functionEntry.name: onStartSync
functionEntry.documentation:
Called when a sync is started by the system.

This method should be used to kick-off the application sync process.
This includes any setup required to fetch the data needed to prepare
the sync, as well as the initial call to
{Toybox::Communications#makeWebRequest makeWebRequest()} to download
the first piece of content. Note that, when using this method,
you must chain your makeWebRequest() calls together manually.
Additionally, you must call {Toybox::Communications#notifySyncProgress notifySyncProgress()}
intermittently to enable sync progress updates to be displayed in
the native user interface for the device. Finally,
{Toybox::Communications#notifySyncComplete notifySyncComplete()} must be
called either when the sync has successfully completed, or if an
error occurs, so that the device can be properly notified that the
sync process is finished.
@since 3.1.0

functionEntry.name: onStopSync
functionEntry.documentation:
Called when an active sync is cancelled.

This method will be called when an active sync is being cancelled by
the user. The app is responsible for calling the
{Toybox::Communications#cancelAllRequests cancelAllRequests()} to
cancel any requests made for a sync process. The app is also responsible
to let the system know that sync has successfully been cancelled by
calling {Toybox::Communications#notifySyncComplete notifySyncComplete()}.
@since 3.1.0

functionEntry.name: toString
functionEntry.documentation:
Convert a Dictionary to a String.

Due to the nature of hash tables, the order of Dictionary elements are
not guaranteed to match the insertion order when converting to a String.
Returns [Toybox::Lang::String] A String representation of the Dictionary

@example
using Toybox.System;
myDict = {
"One" => 1,
"Two" => 2,
"Three" => 3
};
System.println(myDict.get("One")); // prints 1

var myString = myDict.toString();
System.println(myString); // "{Two=>2, One=>1, Three=>}"
System.println(myString.get("One")); // Symbol Not Found Error
System.println(myString.substring(0, 5)); // "{Two="
@see https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hash_table Hash Tables
@since 1.0.1

functionEntry.name: toLongWithBase
functionEntry.documentation:
Convert a String to a Long using a specified base.
base [Toybox::Lang::Object] The base of the input string.

If the value of +base+ is zero, the string content is expected to have
syntax similar to that of integer constants, which includes:
* An optional sign character ('+' or '-')
* An optional prefix for octal or hexadecimal ('0' or '0x')
* A sequence of digits in the prefixed base, or decimal if none was specified.
If the base value is between 2 and 36, the format expected for the
number is valid digits and/or letters that represent integers of
the specified radix (from '0' to 'z' or 'Z' for base 36).
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Long] A Long representation of the String

@example
var myString;
var myNum;

myString = "10";
myNum = myString.toLongWithBase(2); // myNum is 2

myString = "FF";

functionEntry.name: toLong
functionEntry.documentation:
Convert a String to a Long.

If a String is in the numeric form of "123", it can be converted to
a Long. Additional characters after the detected number value will
be ignored. Strings that cannot be interpreted as a Long, or whose
value exceeds that which can be represented in a Long, will result
in a +null+ value.
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Long] A Long representation of the String

@example
var myString;
var myNum;

myString = "123";
myNum = myString.toLong(); // myNum is 123

myString = "3.14"
myNum = myString.toLong(); // myNum is 3

myString = "1200 E. 151st. Street"
myNum = myString.toLong(); // myNum is 1200

myString = "Hello There!"
myNum = myString.toLong(); // null
@since 3.1.0

functionEntry.name: toNumberWithBase
functionEntry.documentation:
Convert a String to a Number using a specified base.
base [Toybox::Lang::Object] The base of the input string.

If the value of +base+ is zero, the string content expected to have
syntax similar to that of integer constants, which includes:
* An optional sign character ('+' or '-')
* An optional prefix for octal or hexadecimal ('0' or '0x')
* A sequence of digits in the prefixed base, or decimal if none was specified.
If the base value is between 2 and 36, the format expected for the
number is valid digits and/or letters that represent integers of
the specified radix (from '0' to 'z' or 'Z' for base 36).
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Number] A Number representation of the String

@example
var myString;
var myNum;

myString = "10";
myNum = myString.toNumberWithBase(2); // myNum is 2

myString = "FF";
myNum = myString.toNumberWithBase(16); // myNum is 255
myNum = myString.toNumberWithBase(0x10); // myNum is 255
@since 1.4.1

myNum = myString.toFloat(); // myNum is 192.167999

myString = "Hello There!"

functionEntry.name: format
functionEntry.documentation:
Format a Number using a formatting String.

The formatting string is similar to that available in +printf+ from the
C stdio library, though the +length+ option is not available:
"%[flags][width][.precision]specifier"
[specifiers]
* *d* or *i* - signed decimal integer
* *e* - scientific notation (mantissa/exponent) using 'e' character
* *E* - scientific notation (mantissa/exponent) using 'E' character
* *f* - decimal floating point
* *o* - signed octal
* *u* - unsigned decimal integer
* *x* - unsigned hexadecimal integer
* *X* - unsigned hexadecimal integer (capital letters)
[flags]
* + - Prepends the result with a plus or minus sign ('+' or '-'), including positive numbers. By default, only negative numbers are preceded with a '-' sign.
* *0* - Left-pads the number with zeros (0) instead of spaces, where padding is specified (see width sub-specifier).
[width]
supports only numbers (* is not supported)
[.precision]
supports only numbers (* is not supported)
Returns [Toybox::Lang::String] A formatted String

@example Formatting time with leading zeros
// Format the time to display "08:03:15"
using Toybox.Lang;
var hours = 8;
var minutes = 3;
var seconds = 15;
var myTime = Lang.format(
"$1$:$2$:$3$",
[hours.format("%02d"), minutes.format("%02d"), seconds.format("%02d")]
);
@see https://forums.garmin.com/showthread.php?255191-Formatted-Output Formatted output forum thread
@since 1.0.0

functionEntry.name: remove
functionEntry.documentation:
Remove a byte from a ByteArray.

If the passed byte is found, the ByteArray size is decreased by one and
elements beyond it are shifted to the next lower index. If the ByteArray
has multiple matches, the matching byte at the lowest index will be
removed but the other matching bytes will not be removed.

If no byte is provided as an argument, the ByteArray will remain unchanged
and +remove()+ will return +false+.
byte [Toybox::Lang::Number, Toybox::Lang::Char] The byte to

remove from the ByteArray
@throws [Toybox::Lang::UnexpectedTypeException] Thrown if a type other
than {Toybox::Lang::Number Number} or {Toybox::Lang::Char Char}
is provided
@throws [Toybox::Lang::ValueOutOfBoundsException] Thrown if a
{Toybox::Lang::Number Number} greater than 255 or less than -128
is provided, or if a {Toybox::Lang::Char Char} with a code point
greater than 127 is provided. Negative numbers provided are
interpreted as the positive 8-bit unsigned equivalent when
searching the ByteArray.
Returns [Toybox::Lang::Boolean] Returns +true+ if instances of the byte are

found, otherwise +false+
@since 3.0.0

@throws [Toybox::Lang::UnexpectedTypeException] Thrown if a type other

@throws [Toybox::Lang::ValueOutOfBoundsException] Thrown if a

greater than 127 is provided. Negative numbers provided
